        <h2 class="">How are coffee beans processed?</h2>
        <div class="column-list">
            <div style="width:56.25%" class="column">
                <p class="">Once the coffee cherries are harvested, the beans need to be separated
                    from the fruit and dried. There are two main methods for processing coffee beans:
                    the dry method and the wet method.</p>
                <p class=""></p>
            </div>
            <div style="width:43.75000000000001%" class="column">
                <figure class="image">
                    <a href="Coffee%20Beans%206acd225ae6b247aba18a2841e5c148e2/Untitled%201.png">
                        <img style="width:700px" src="Coffee%20Beans%206acd225ae6b247aba18a2841e5c148e2/Untitled%201.png"/>
                    </a>
                </figure>
            </div>
        </div>
        <p class="">The dry method, also known as the natural method,
            involves laying the coffee cherries out in the sun to dry for
            several weeks. During this time, the cherries are raked and turned
            to ensure even drying. Once the cherries are dry, they are hulled
            to remove the outer layers of fruit and parchment, leaving behind
            the green coffee beans.</p>
        <figure class="callout" style="white-space:pre-wrap;display:flex">
            <div style="font-size:1.5em">
                <span class="icon">ðŸ’¡</span>
            </div>
            <div style="width:100%">The wet method,
                also known as the washed method, involves
                removing the outer layers of fruit from
                the coffee cherries using water. The cherries
                are first pulped to remove the fruit, and then
                the beans are soaked in water to remove any remaining
                pulp. The beans are then dried, either in the sun or
                using mechanical dryers.</div>
        </figure>
        <p class="">After the beans are dried, they are sorted
            and graded based on their size, shape, and color.
            Higher quality beans are typically larger, denser,
            and more uniform in color.</p>
        <h2 class="">How are coffee beans roasted?</h2>
        <p class="">Roasting is a crucial step in the coffee-making process,
            as it brings out the flavor and aroma of the beans.
            During the roasting process, the beans are heated
            to high temperatures, causing them to expand and release
            their oils and flavors.</p>
        <p class="">There are three main types of coffee roasts: light, medium,
            and dark. Light roasts are roasted for a shorter amount of time and
            have a lighter color and more acidic flavor. Medium roasts are roasted
            for slightly longer and have a more balanced flavor and aroma. Dark
            roasts are roasted for the longest amount of time and have a bold, smoky flavor with less acidity.</p>
